one of the most frequent surnames in Wallonia.","English: variant of   Marton  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mártain</b>, ‘descendant of Martin’ (compare 1 above). Otherwise, a shortened form of   Gilmartin   or   McMartin  ; sometimes also spelled <i>Martyn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Marczewski","meanings":["Polish: habitational name for someone from Marcewo (formerly also <i>Marczewo</i>) in Greater Poland Voivodeship. Alternatively, a derivative of the personal name <i>Marc</i>, <i>Marcz</i>, a pet form of <i>Marcin</i>, <i>Marek</i> (see   Martin  ,   Mark  )."]},{"name":"Marciniak","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Eugeniusz, Ewa, Agnieszka, Bartosz, Boleslaw, Ignatius, Jaroslaw, Jerzy, Krystyna, Ryszard, Slawomir, Stanislawa.","Polish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Marcin</i> (see   Martin  )."]},{"name":"Marak","meanings":["Czech:","(<b>Marák</b>): from a pet form of the personal names   Martin   or   Marek  .","(<b>Mařák</b>): metronymic from the female personal name <i>Máří</i>, Czech form of   Maria  . It may also denoted the husband of a woman named <i>Máří</i>."]},{"name":"Machain","meanings":["Basque: Castilianized form of <b>Matxain</b>, a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with a diminutive of the personal name   Martin  ."]},{"name":"Maertens","meanings":["Flemish and Dutch: patronymic from the personal name <i>Maerten</i>, a variant of   Martin  .","North German (<b>Märtens</b>): see   Martens  ."]},{"name":"Marcin","meanings":["Slovak, Rusyn (from Slovakia), and Polish: from <i>Marcin</i>, a personal name equivalent to   Martin  . In Poland this is the most usual form as a personal name, but the surname is very rare there, while in Slovakia, where <i>Marcin</i> is a dialect form of the name <i>Martin</i>, the situation is opposite.","American shortened form of Polish   Marcinkiewicz   and other derivatives of the personal name <i>Marcin</i> (see 1 above).","In some cases possibly also French: from a vernacular form of the personal name <i>Marcien</i>, derived from the Latin surname <i>Marcianus</i>, popularized through the cult of a local saint."]},{"name":"Macho","meanings":["Spanish: nickname from <i>macho</i> ‘male; mule’ (from Latin <i>masculus</i> ‘male, masculine’), applied either to denote a virile, strong man or alternatively an idiot.","Spanish: possibly also a nickname for a forceful person or a metonymic occupational name for a smith, from <i>macho</i> ‘sledgehammer’ (from Latin <i>marculus</i> ‘hammer’).","Slovak: from a derivative of the personal name   Martin  ."]},{"name":"Marcinowski","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Aleksander, Bogdan, Jerzy, Zbigniew, Zigmund.","Polish: habitational name for someone from any of the places called Marcinów, Marcinowa, Marcinowice, or any of numerous other places in Poland named with the personal name <i>Marcin</i> (see   Martin  )."]},{"name":"Marcinkiewicz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Henryk, Beata, Elzbieta, Janina.","Polish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Marcinek</i>, a petform of <i>Marcin</i> (see   Martin  )."]},{"name":"Mar","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Gim, Wai, Fong, Hong, Man Chung, Moo, Mun, Quon, Wing, Yat, Bok, Chun.","Spanish, Portuguese, Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Catalan: topographic name for someone living by the sea, from <i>mar</i> ‘sea’ (from Latin <i>mare</i>).","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>mar(w)</i> ‘tender, delicate’, or an altered form of <b>Mahr</b>, a topographic name from <i>mar</i> ‘lake, swamp, stagnant water’."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Ann Martin was born in 1344, in Forfarshire, Scotland. She married John Brown in 1367, in Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire